# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: vis-viva
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:vis-viva/alternating-series-test] In mathematical analysis, the **alternating series test** proves that an alternating series is convergent when its terms decrease monotonically in absolute value and approach zero in the limit.
[src:vis-viva/alternating-series-test] The test was devised by Gottfried Leibniz and is sometimes known as **Leibniz's test**, **Leibniz's rule**, or the **Leibniz criterion**.
[src:vis-viva/alternating-series-test] The test is only sufficient, not necessary, so some convergent alternating series may fail the first part of the test.
[src:vis-viva/alternating-series-test] For a generalization, see Dirichlet's test.
[src:vis-viva/alternating-series-test] Leibniz discussed the criterion in his unpublished *De quadratura arithmetica* of 1676 and shared his result with Jakob Hermann in June 1705 and with Johann Bernoulli in October, 1713.
[src:vis-viva/alternating-series-test] where either all *a**n* are positive or all *a**n* are negative, is called an alternating series.
[src:vis-viva/alternating-series-test] both because *a**n* decreases monotonically with *n*.
[src:vis-viva/alternating-series-test] Now, note that *a**1* − *a**2* is a lower bound of the monotonically decreasing sequence *S**2m+1*, the monotone convergence theorem then implies that this sequence converges as *m* approaches infinity.
[src:vis-viva/alternating-series-test] Similarly, the sequence of even partial sum converges too.
[src:vis-viva/alternating-series-test] This means the partial sums of an alternating series also "alternates" above and below the final limit.
[src:vis-viva/alternating-series-test] More precisely, when there is an odd (even) number of terms, i.e. the last term is a plus (minus) term, then the partial sum is above (below) the final limit.
[src:vis-viva/alternating-series-test] This understanding leads immediately to an error bound of partial sums, shown below.
[src:vis-viva/alternating-series-test] We would like to show $\left|S_{k}-L\right|\leq a_{k+1}\!$ by splitting into two cases.
[src:vis-viva/alternating-series-test] Both cases rely essentially on the last inequality derived in the previous proof.
[src:vis-viva/alternating-series-test] Philip Calabrese (1962) and Richard Johnsonbaugh (1979) have found tighter bounds.
[src:vis-viva/alternating-series-test] meets both conditions for the alternating series test and converges.
[src:vis-viva/alternating-series-test] Both conditions in the test must be met for the conclusion to be true.
[src:vis-viva/alternating-series-test] The signs are alternating and the terms tend to zero.
[src:vis-viva/alternating-series-test] However, monotonicity is not present and we cannot apply the test.
[src:vis-viva/alternating-series-test] Leibniz test's monotonicity is not a necessary condition, thus the test itself is only sufficient, but not necessary.
[src:vis-viva/alternating-series-test] In fact, for every monotonic series it is possible to obtain an infinite number of nonmonotonic series that converge to the same sum by permuting its terms with permutations satisfying the condition in Agnew's theorem.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] It is generally accepted that Lavoisier's great accomplishments in chemistry stem largely from his changing the science from a qualitative to a quantitative one.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] Lavoisier is noted for his discovery of the role oxygen plays in combustion, opposing the prior phlogiston theory of combustion.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] He named oxygen (1778), recognizing it as an element, and also recognized hydrogen as an element (1783).
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] Lavoisier helped construct the metric system, wrote the first extensive list of elements, in which he predicted the existence of silicon, and helped to reform chemical nomenclature.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] His wife and laboratory assistant, Marie-Anne Paulze Lavoisier, became a renowned chemist in her own right, and worked with him to develop the metric system of measurements.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] Lavoisier was a powerful member of a number of aristocratic councils, and an administrator of the *Ferme générale*.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] The *Ferme générale* was one of the most hated components of the *Ancien Régime* because of the profits it took at the expense of the state, the secrecy of the terms of its contracts, and the violence of its armed agents.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] All of these political and economic activities enabled him to fund his scientific research.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] At the height of the French Revolution, he was charged with tax fraud and selling adulterated tobacco, and was guillotined despite appeals to spare his life in recognition of his contributions to science.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] A year and a half later, he was exonerated by the French government.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] Antoine-Laurent Lavoisier was born to a wealthy family of the nobility in Paris on 26 August 1743.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] The son of an attorney at the Parlement of Paris, he inherited a large fortune at the age of five upon the death of his mother.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] Lavoisier began his schooling at the Collège des Quatre-Nations, University of Paris (also known as the Collège Mazarin) in Paris in 1754 at the age of 11.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] In his last two years (1760–1761) at the school, his scientific interests were aroused, and he studied chemistry, botany, astronomy, and mathematics.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] In the philosophy class he came under the tutelage of Abbé Nicolas Louis de Lacaille, a distinguished mathematician and observational astronomer who imbued the young Lavoisier with an interest in meteorological observation, an enthusiasm which never left him.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] Lavoisier entered the school of law, where he received a bachelor's degree in 1763 and a licentiate in 1764.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] Lavoisier received a law degree and was admitted to the bar, but never practiced as a lawyer.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] However, he continued his scientific education in his spare time.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] Lavoisier's education was filled with the ideals of the French Enlightenment of the time, and he was fascinated by Pierre Macquer's dictionary of chemistry.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] He attended lectures in the natural sciences.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] Lavoisier's devotion and passion for chemistry were largely influenced by Étienne Condillac, a prominent French scholar of the 18th century.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] His first chemical publication appeared in 1764.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] From 1763 to 1767, he studied geology under Jean-Étienne Guettard.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] In collaboration with Guettard, Lavoisier worked on a geological survey of Alsace–Lorraine in June 1767.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] In 1764 he read his first paper to the French Academy of Sciences, France's most elite scientific society, on the chemical and physical properties of gypsum (hydrated calcium sulfate), and in 1766 he was awarded a gold medal by the King for an essay on the problems of urban street lighting.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] In 1768 Lavoisier received a provisional appointment to the Academy of Sciences.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] In 1769, he worked on the first geological map of France.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] While Lavoisier is commonly known for his contributions to the sciences, he also dedicated a significant portion of his fortune and work toward benefitting the public.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] Lavoisier was a humanitarian—he cared deeply about the people in his country and often concerned himself with improving the livelihood of the population by agriculture, industry, and the sciences.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] The first instance of this occurred in 1765, when he submitted an essay on improving urban street lighting to the French Academy of Sciences.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] Three years later in 1768, he focused on a new project to design an aqueduct.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] The goal was to bring water from the river Yvette into Paris so that the citizens could have clean drinking water.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] But, since the construction never commenced, he instead turned his focus to purifying the water from the Seine.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] This was the project that interested Lavoisier in the chemistry of water and public sanitation duties.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] Additionally, he was interested in air quality and spent some time studying the health risks associated with gunpowder's effect on the air.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] In 1772, he performed a study on how to reconstruct the Hôtel-Dieu hospital, after it had been damaged by fire, in a way that would allow proper ventilation and clean air throughout.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] At the time, the prisons in Paris were known to be largely unlivable and the prisoners' treatment inhumane.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] Lavoisier took part in investigations in 1780 (and again in 1791) on the hygiene in prisons and had made suggestions to improve living conditions, suggestions which were largely ignored.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] Once a part of the academy, Lavoisier also held his own competitions to push the direction of research towards bettering the public and his own work.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] Lavoisier had a vision of public education having roots in "scientific sociability" and philanthropy.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] Lavoisier gained a vast majority of his income through buying stock in the General Farm, which allowed him to work on science full-time, live comfortably, and allowed him to contribute financially to better the community.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] He also pushed for public education in the sciences.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] He founded two organizations, Lycée and Musée des Arts et Métiers, which were created to serve as educational tools for the public.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] Funded by the wealthy and noble, the Lycée regularly taught courses to the public beginning in 1793.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] At the age of 26, around the time he was elected to the Academy of Sciences, Lavoisier bought a share in the *Ferme générale*, a tax farming financial company which advanced the estimated tax revenue to the royal government in return for the right to collect the taxes.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] On behalf of the Ferme générale Lavoisier commissioned the building of a wall around Paris so that customs duties could be collected from those transporting goods into and out of the city.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] His participation in the collection of its taxes did not help his reputation when the Reign of Terror began in France, as taxes and poor government reform were the primary motivators during the French Revolution.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] Lavoisier consolidated his social and economic position when, in 1771 at age 28, he married Marie-Anne Pierrette Paulze, the 13-year-old daughter of a senior member of the *Ferme générale*.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] She was to play an important part in Lavoisier's scientific career—notably, she translated English documents for him, including Richard Kirwan's *Essay on Phlogiston* and Joseph Priestley's research.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] In addition, she assisted him in the laboratory and created many sketches and carved engravings of the laboratory instruments used by Lavoisier and his colleagues for their scientific works.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] Madame Lavoisier edited and published Antoine's memoirs (whether any English translations of those memoirs have survived is unknown as of today) and hosted parties at which eminent scientists discussed ideas and problems related to chemistry.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] A portrait of Antoine and Marie-Anne Lavoisier was painted by the famed artist Jacques-Louis David.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] Completed in 1788 on the eve of the Revolution, the painting was denied a customary public display at the Paris Salon for fear that it might inflame anti-aristocratic passions.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] For three years following his entry into the *Ferme générale*, Lavoisier's scientific activity diminished somewhat, for much of his time was taken up with official *Ferme générale* business.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] He did, however, present one important memoir to the Academy of Sciences during this period, on the supposed conversion of water into earth by evaporation.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] He also attempted to introduce reforms in the French monetary and taxation system to help the peasants.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] The Farmers General held a monopoly of the production, import and sale of tobacco in France, and the taxes they levied on tobacco brought revenues of 30 million livres a year.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] This revenue began to fall because of a growing black market in tobacco that was smuggled and adulterated, most commonly with ash and water.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] Lavoisier also noticed that the addition of a small amount of ash improved the flavour of tobacco.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] Of one vendor selling adulterated goods, he wrote "His tobacco enjoys a very good reputation in the province... the very small proportion of ash that is added gives it a particularly pungent flavour that consumers look for.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] Perhaps the Farm could gain some advantage by adding a bit of this liquid mixture when the tobacco is fabricated." Lavoisier also found that while adding a lot of water to bulk the tobacco up would cause it to ferment and smell bad, the addition of a very small amount improved the product.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] Thereafter the factories of the Farmers General added, as he recommended, a consistent 6.3% of water by volume to the tobacco they processed.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] To allow for this addition, the Farmers General delivered to retailers seventeen ounces of tobacco while only charging for sixteen.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] To ensure that only these authorised amounts were added, and to exclude the black market, Lavoisier saw to it that a watertight system of checks, accounts, supervision and testing made it very difficult for retailers to source contraband tobacco or to improve their profits by bulking it up.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] He was energetic and rigorous in implementing this, and the systems he introduced were deeply unpopular with the tobacco retailers across the country.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] This unpopularity was to have consequences for him during the French Revolution.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] Lavoisier urged the establishment of a Royal Commission on Agriculture.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] He then served as its Secretary and spent considerable sums of his own money in order to improve the agricultural yields in the Sologne, an area where farmland was of poor quality.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] The humidity of the region often led to a blight of the rye harvest, causing outbreaks of ergotism among the population.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] In 1788 Lavoisier presented a report to the Commission detailing ten years of efforts on his experimental farm to introduce new crops and types of livestock.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] His conclusion was that despite the possibilities of agricultural reforms, the tax system left tenant farmers with so little that it was unrealistic to expect them to change their traditional practices.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] Lavoisier's researches on combustion were carried out in the midst of a very busy schedule of public and private duties, especially in connection with the *Ferme Générale*.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] There were also innumerable reports for and committees of the Academy of Sciences to investigate specific problems on order of the royal government.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] Lavoisier, whose organizing skills were outstanding, frequently landed the task of writing up such official reports.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] In 1775 he was made one of four commissioners of gunpowder appointed to replace a private company, similar to the Ferme Générale, which had proved unsatisfactory in supplying France with its munitions requirements.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] As a result of his efforts, both the quantity and quality of French gunpowder greatly improved, and it became a source of revenue for the government.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] His appointment to the Gunpowder Commission brought one great benefit to Lavoisier's scientific career as well.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] As a commissioner, he enjoyed both a house and a laboratory in the Royal Arsenal.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] Here he lived and worked between 1775 and 1792.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] In June 1791, Lavoisier made a loan of 71,000 livres to Pierre Samuel du Pont de Nemours to buy a printing works so that du Pont could publish a newspaper, *La Correspondance Patriotique*.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] The plan was for this to include both reports of debates in the National Constituent Assembly as well as papers from the Academy of Sciences.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] The revolution quickly disrupted the elder du Pont's first newspaper, but his son E.I. du Pont soon launched *Le Republicain* and published Lavoisier's latest chemistry texts.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] Lavoisier also chaired the commission set up to establish a uniform system of weights and measures which in March 1791 recommended the adoption of the metric system.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] The new system of weights and measures was adopted by the Convention on 1 August 1793.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] Lavoisier was one of the 27 Farmers General who, by order of the convention, were all to be detained.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] Although temporarily going into hiding, on 30 November 1793 he handed himself into the Port Royal convent for questioning.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] He claimed he had not operated on this commission for many years, having instead devoted himself to science.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] Lavoisier himself was removed from the commission on weights and measures on 23 December 1793, together with mathematician Pierre-Simon Laplace and several other members, for political reasons.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] One of his last major works was a proposal to the National Convention for the reform of French education.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] He also intervened on behalf of a number of foreign-born scientists including mathematician Joseph Louis Lagrange, helping to exempt them from a mandate stripping all foreigners of possessions and freedom.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] As the French Revolution gained momentum, attacks mounted on the deeply unpopular *Ferme générale*, and it was eventually abolished in March 1791.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] In 1792 Lavoisier was forced to resign from his post on the Gunpowder Commission and to move from his house and laboratory at the Royal Arsenal.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] On 8 August 1793, all the learned societies, including the Academy of Sciences, were suppressed at the request of Abbé Grégoire.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] On 24 November 1793, the arrest of all the former tax farmers was ordered.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] Lavoisier and the other Farmers General faced nine accusations of defrauding the state of money owed to it, and of adding water to tobacco before selling it.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] Lavoisier drafted their defense, refuting the financial accusations, reminding the court of how they had maintained a consistently high quality of tobacco.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] The court, however, was inclined to believe that by condemning them and seizing the goods of the Farmers General, it would recover huge sums for the state.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] Lavoisier was convicted and guillotined on 8 May 1794 in Paris, at the age of 50, along with his 27 co-defendants.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] A year and a half after his execution, Lavoisier was completely exonerated by the French government.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] During the White Terror, his belongings were delivered to his widow.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] A brief note was included, reading "To the widow of Lavoisier, who was falsely convicted".
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] An apocryphal story exists regarding Lavoisier's execution in which the scientist blinked his eyes to demonstrate that the head retained some consciousness after being severed.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] Some variants of the story include Joseph-Louis Lagrange as being the scientist to observe and record Lavoisier's blinking.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] This story was not recorded in contemporary accounts of Lavoisier's death, and the execution site was too removed from the public for Lagrange to have viewed Lavoisier's alleged experiment.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] The story likely originated in a 1990s Discovery Channel documentary about guillotines and then subsequently spread online, becoming what one source describes as an urban legend.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] Contrary to prevailing thought at the time, Lavoisier theorized that common air, or one of its components, combines with substances when they are burned.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] He demonstrated this through experiment.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] During late 1772 Lavoisier turned his attention to the phenomenon of combustion, the topic on which he was to make his most significant contribution to science.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] He reported the results of his first experiments on combustion in a note to the Academy on 20 October, in which he reported that when phosphorus burned, it combined with a large quantity of air to produce acid spirit of phosphorus, and that the phosphorus increased in weight on burning.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] During 1773 Lavoisier determined to review thoroughly the literature on air, particularly "fixed air," and to repeat many of the experiments of other workers in the field.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] He published an account of this review in 1774 in a book entitled *Opuscules physiques et chimiques* (Physical and Chemical Essays).
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] In the course of this review, he made his first full study of the work of Joseph Black, the Scottish chemist who had carried out a series of classic quantitative experiments on the mild and caustic alkalies.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] Lavoisier recognized that Black's fixed air was identical with the air evolved when metal calces were reduced with charcoal and even suggested that the air which combined with metals on calcination and increased the weight might be Black's fixed air, that is, CO2.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] In the spring of 1774, Lavoisier carried out experiments on the calcination of tin and lead in sealed vessels, the results of which conclusively confirmed that the increase in weight of metals in combustion was due to combination with air.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] But the question remained about whether it was in combination with common atmospheric air or with only a part of atmospheric air.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] In October the English chemist Joseph Priestley visited Paris, where he met Lavoisier and told him of the air which he had produced by heating the red calx of mercury with a burning glass and which had supported combustion with extreme vigor.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] Priestley at this time was unsure of the nature of this gas, but he felt that it was an especially pure form of common air.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] Lavoisier carried out his own research on this peculiar substance.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] The result was his memoir *On the Nature of the Principle Which Combines with Metals during Their Calcination and Increases Their Weight*, read to the Academy on 26 April 1775 (commonly referred to as the Easter Memoir).
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] In the original memoir, Lavoisier showed that the mercury calx was a true metallic calx in that it could be reduced with charcoal, giving off Black's fixed air in the process.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] When reduced without charcoal, it gave off an air which supported respiration and combustion in an enhanced way.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] He concluded that this was just a pure form of common air and that it was the air itself "undivided, without alteration, without decomposition" which combined with metals on calcination.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] After returning from Paris, Priestley took up once again his investigation of the air from mercury calx.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] His results now showed that this air was not just an especially pure form of common air but was "five or six times better than common air, for the purpose of respiration, inflammation, and ... every other use of common air".
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] He called the air dephlogisticated air, as he thought it was common air deprived of its phlogiston.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] Since it was therefore in a state to absorb a much greater quantity of phlogiston given off by burning bodies and respiring animals, the greatly enhanced combustion of substances and the greater ease of breathing in this air were explained.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] Lavoisier's researches included some of the first truly quantitative chemical experiments.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] He carefully weighed the reactants and products of a chemical reaction in a sealed glass vessel so that no gases could escape, which was a crucial step in the advancement of chemistry.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] In 1774, he showed that, although matter can change its state in a chemical reaction, the total mass of matter is the same at the end as at the beginning of every chemical change.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] Thus, for instance, if a piece of wood is burned to ashes, the total mass remains unchanged if gaseous reactants and products are included.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] Lavoisier's experiments supported the law of conservation of mass.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] Lavoisier, together with Louis-Bernard Guyton de Morveau, Claude-Louis Berthollet, and Antoine François de Fourcroy, submitted a new program for the reforms of chemical nomenclature to the academy in 1787, for there was virtually no rational system of chemical nomenclature at this time.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] This work, titled *Méthode de nomenclature chimique* (*Method of Chemical Nomenclature*, 1787), introduced a new system which was tied inextricably to Lavoisier's new oxygen theory of chemistry.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] The classical elements of earth, air, fire, and water were discarded, and instead some 33 substances which could not be decomposed into simpler substances by any known chemical means were provisionally listed as elements.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] Similarly, salts of the "ic" acids were given the terminal letters "ate," as in copper sulfate, whereas the salts of the "ous" acids terminated with the suffix "ite," as in copper sulfite.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] The total effect of the new nomenclature can be gauged by comparing the new name "copper sulfate" with the old term "vitriol of Venus." Lavoisier's new nomenclature spread throughout Europe and to the United States and became common use in the field of chemistry.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] This marked the beginning of the anti-phlogistic approach to the field.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] Lavoisier is commonly cited as a central contributor to the chemical revolution.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] His precise measurements and meticulous keeping of balance sheets throughout his experiment were vital to the widespread acceptance of the law of conservation of mass.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] His introduction of new terminology, a binomial system modeled after that of Linnaeus, also helps to mark the dramatic changes in the field which are referred to generally as the chemical revolution.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] Lavoisier encountered much opposition in trying to change the field, especially from British phlogistic scientists.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] Joseph Priestley, Richard Kirwan, James Keir, and William Nicholson, among others, argued that quantification of substances did not imply conservation of mass.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] Rather than reporting factual evidence, opposition claimed Lavoisier was misinterpreting the implications of his research.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] One of Lavoisier's allies, Jean Baptiste Biot, wrote of Lavoisier's methodology, "one felt the necessity of linking accuracy in experiments to rigor of reasoning." His opposition argued that precision in experimentation did not imply precision in inferences and reasoning.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] Despite opposition, Lavoisier continued to use precise instrumentation to convince other chemists of his conclusions, often results to five to eight decimal places.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] The "official" version of Lavoisier's Easter Memoir appeared in 1778.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] In the intervening period, Lavoisier had ample time to repeat some of Priestley's latest experiments and perform some new ones of his own.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] In addition to studying Priestley's dephlogisticated air, he studied more thoroughly the residual air after metals had been calcined.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] He showed that this residual air supported neither combustion nor respiration and that approximately five volumes of this air added to one volume of the dephlogisticated air gave common atmospheric air.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] Common air was then a mixture of two distinct chemical species with quite different properties.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] Thus when the revised version of the Easter Memoir was published in 1778, Lavoisier no longer stated that the principle which combined with metals on calcination was just common air but "nothing else than the healthiest and purest part of the air" or the "eminently respirable part of the air".
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] The same year he coined the name oxygen for this constituent of the air, from the Greek words meaning "acid former".
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] He was struck by the fact that the combustion products of such nonmetals as sulfur, phosphorus, charcoal, and nitrogen were acidic.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] He held that all acids contained oxygen and that oxygen was therefore the acidifying principle.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] Lavoisier's chemical research between 1772 and 1778 was largely concerned with developing his own new theory of combustion.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] In 1783 he read to the academy his paper entitled *Réflexions sur le phlogistique* (Reflections on Phlogiston), a full-scale attack on the current phlogiston theory of combustion.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] That year Lavoisier also began a series of experiments on the composition of water which were to prove an important capstone to his combustion theory and win many converts to it.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] Many investigators had been experimenting with the combination of Henry Cavendish's inflammable air, now known as hydrogen, with "dephlogisticated air" (air in the process of combustion, now known to be oxygen) by electrically sparking mixtures of the gases.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] All of the researchers noted Cavendish's production of pure water by burning hydrogen in oxygen, but they interpreted the reaction in varying ways within the framework of phlogiston theory.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] Lavoisier learned of Cavendish's experiment in June 1783 via Charles Blagden (before the results were published in 1784), and immediately recognized water as the oxide of a "hydrogenerative" gas.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] In cooperation with Laplace, Lavoisier synthesized water by burning jets of hydrogen and oxygen in a bell jar over mercury.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] The quantitative results were good enough to support the contention that water was not an element, as had been thought for over 2,000 years, but a compound of two gases, hydrogen and oxygen.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] The interpretation of water as a compound explained the inflammable air generated from dissolving metals in acids (hydrogen produced when water decomposes) and the reduction of calces by inflammable air (a combination of gas from calx with hydrogen to form water).
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] Despite these experiments, Lavoisier's antiphlogistic approach remained unaccepted by many other chemists.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] Lavoisier labored to provide definitive proof of the composition of water, attempting to use this in support of his theory.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] Working with Jean-Baptiste Meusnier, Lavoisier passed water through a red-hot iron gun barrel, allowing the oxygen to form an oxide with the iron and the hydrogen to emerge from the end of the pipe.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] He submitted his findings of the composition of water to the Académie des Sciences in April 1784, reporting his figures to eight decimal places.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] Opposition responded to this further experimentation by stating that Lavoisier continued to draw the incorrect conclusions and that his experiment demonstrated the displacement of phlogiston from iron by the combination of water with the metal.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] Lavoisier developed a new apparatus which used a pneumatic trough, a set of balances, a thermometer, and a barometer, all calibrated carefully.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] Thirty savants were invited to witness the decomposition and synthesis of water using this apparatus, convincing many who attended of the correctness of Lavoisier's theories.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] This demonstration established water as a compound of oxygen and hydrogen with great certainty for those who viewed it.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] The dissemination of the experiment, however, proved subpar, as it lacked the details to properly display the amount of precision taken in the measurements.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] The paper ended with a hasty statement that the experiment was "more than sufficient to lay hold of the certainty of the proposition" of the composition of water and stated that the methods used in the experiment would unite chemistry with the other physical sciences and advance discoveries.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] Lavoisier employed the new nomenclature in his *Traité élémentaire de chimie* (*Elementary Treatise on Chemistry*), published in 1789.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] This work represents the synthesis of Lavoisier's contribution to chemistry and can be considered the first modern textbook on the subject.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] The core of the work was the oxygen theory, and the work became a most effective vehicle for the transmission of the new doctrines.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] It presented a unified view of new theories of chemistry, contained a clear statement of the law of conservation of mass, and denied the existence of phlogiston.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] This text clarified the concept of an element as a substance that could not be broken down by any known method of chemical analysis and presented Lavoisier's theory of the formation of chemical compounds from elements.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] It remains a classic in the history of science.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] While many leading chemists of the time refused to accept Lavoisier's new ideas, demand for *Traité élémentaire* as a textbook in Edinburgh was sufficient to merit translation into English within about a year of its French publication.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] In any event, the *Traité élémentaire* was sufficiently sound to convince the next generation.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] The relationship between combustion and respiration had long been recognized from the essential role which air played in both processes.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] Lavoisier was almost obliged, therefore, to extend his new theory of combustion to include the area of respiration physiology.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] His first memoirs on this topic were read to the Academy of Sciences in 1777, but his most significant contribution to this field was made in the winter of 1782–1783 in association with Laplace.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] The result of this work was published in a memoir, "On Heat." Lavoisier and Laplace designed an ice calorimeter apparatus for measuring the amount of heat given off during combustion or respiration.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] The outer shell of the calorimeter was packed with snow, which melted to maintain a constant temperature of 0 °C around an inner shell filled with ice.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] Lavoisier stated, *"la respiration est donc une combustion,"* that is, respiratory gas exchange is a combustion, like that of a candle burning.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] This continuous slow combustion, which they supposed took place in the lungs, enabled the living animal to maintain its body temperature above that of its surroundings, thus accounting for the puzzling phenomenon of animal heat.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] Lavoisier continued these respiration experiments in 1789–1790 in cooperation with Armand Seguin.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] They designed an ambitious set of experiments to study the whole process of body metabolism and respiration using Seguin as a human guinea pig in the experiments.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] Their work was only partially completed and published because of the Revolution's disruption, but Lavoisier's pioneering work in this field inspired similar research on physiological processes for generations.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] Lavoisier's fundamental contributions to chemistry were a result of a conscious effort to fit all experiments into the framework of a single theory.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] He established the consistent use of the chemical balance, used oxygen to overthrow the phlogiston theory, and developed a new system of chemical nomenclature which held that oxygen was an essential constituent of all acids (which later turned out to be erroneous).
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] Lavoisier also did early research in physical chemistry and thermodynamics in joint experiments with Laplace.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] They used a calorimeter to estimate the heat evolved per unit of carbon dioxide produced, eventually finding the same ratio for a flame and animals, indicating that animals produced energy by a type of combustion reaction.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] Lavoisier also contributed to early ideas on composition and chemical changes by stating the radical theory, believing that radicals, which function as a single group in a chemical process, combine with oxygen in reactions.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] He also introduced the possibility of allotropy in chemical elements when he discovered that diamond is a crystalline form of carbon.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] He was also responsible for the construction of the gasometer, an expensive instrument he used at his demonstrations.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] While he used his gasometer exclusively for these, he also created smaller, cheaper, more practical gasometers that worked with a sufficient degree of precision that more chemists could recreate.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] Overall, his contributions are considered the most important in advancing chemistry to the level reached in physics and mathematics during the 18th century.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] Following his death, a collection comprising most of his scientific manuscripts and instruments was established by his relatives at the Château de la Canière in Puy-de-Dôme.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] Mount Lavoisier in New Zealand's Paparoa Range was named after him in 1970 by the Department of Scientific and Industrial Research.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] In the Breaking Bad season 5 episode “Say My Name” (episode 7), Walter White tells Todd Alquist, “I don’t need you to be Antoine Lavoisier,” meaning that Todd does not need to be an expert to assist with cooking methamphetamine.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] During his lifetime, Lavoisier was awarded a gold medal by the King of France for his work on urban street lighting (1766), and was appointed to the French Academy of Sciences (1768).
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] He was elected as a member of the American Philosophical Society in 1775.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] Lavoisier's work was recognized as an International Historic Chemical Landmark by the American Chemical Society, Académie des sciences de L'institut de France and the Société Chimique de France in 1999.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] The prize, which includes a medal, is given jointly by the Fondation de la Maison de la Chimie in Paris, France and the Science History Institute in Philadelphia, PA, USA.
[src:vis-viva/antoine-lavoisier] "Lavoisier's "Reflections on phlogiston" II: On the nature of heat".
[src:vis-viva/benjamin-thompson] Colonel **Sir Benjamin Thompson, Count Rumford**, FRS (26 March 1753 – 21 August 1814), was an American-born British military officer, scientist and inventor.
[src:vis-viva/benjamin-thompson] Born in Woburn, Massachusetts, he supported the Loyalist cause during the American War of Independence, commanding the King's American Dragoons during the conflict.
[src:vis-viva/benjamin-thompson] After the war ended in 1783, Thompson moved to London, where he was recognised for his administrative talents and received a knighthood from George III in 1784.
[src:vis-viva/benjamin-thompson] A prolific scientist and inventor, Thompson also created several new warship designs.
[src:vis-viva/benjamin-thompson] He subsequently moved to the Electorate of Bavaria and entered into the employ of the Bavarian government, heavily reorganising the Bavarian Army.
[src:vis-viva/benjamin-thompson] Thompson was rewarded for his efforts by being made an Imperial Count in 1792 before dying in Paris in 1814.
[src:vis-viva/benjamin-thompson] Thompson was born in rural Woburn, in the Province of Massachusetts Bay, on 26 March 1753; his birthplace is preserved as a museum.
[src:vis-viva/benjamin-thompson] He was educated mainly at the village school, although he sometimes walked almost ten miles to Cambridge with the older Loammi Baldwin to attend lectures by Professor John Winthrop of Harvard College.
[src:vis-viva/benjamin-thompson] At the age of 13 he was apprenticed to John Appleton, a merchant of nearby Salem.
[src:vis-viva/benjamin-thompson] Thompson excelled at his trade, and coming in contact with refined and well educated people for the first time, adopted many of their characteristics including an interest in science.
[src:vis-viva/benjamin-thompson] While recuperating in Woburn in 1769 from an injury, Thompson conducted his first experiments studying the nature of heat and began to correspond with Baldwin and others about them.
[src:vis-viva/benjamin-thompson] Later that year he worked several months for a Boston shopkeeper and then apprenticed himself briefly, and unsuccessfully, to a doctor in Woburn.
[src:vis-viva/benjamin-thompson] Thompson's prospects were dim in 1772 but in that year they changed abruptly.
[src:vis-viva/benjamin-thompson] He met, charmed and married a rich and well-connected widow, an heiress named Sarah Rolfe (née Walker).
[src:vis-viva/benjamin-thompson] Her father was a minister, and her late husband left her property at Rumford, Province of New Hampshire, which is today in the modern city of Concord.
[src:vis-viva/benjamin-thompson] They moved to Portsmouth, and through his wife's influence with the governor, he was appointed a major in the New Hampshire Militia.
[src:vis-viva/benjamin-thompson] Their child (also named Sarah) was born in 1774.
[src:vis-viva/benjamin-thompson] Following the outbreak of the American Revolutionary War in 1775, Thompson, by now a wealthy and influential landowner, came out as a Loyalist.
[src:vis-viva/benjamin-thompson] He was soon using his connections in the colonial militia to recruit and arm Loyalists seeking to fight alongside the British against rebel forces, which earned him the enmity of Patriots in New Hampshire.
[src:vis-viva/benjamin-thompson] Thompson was stripped of his militia commission and a Patriot mob attacked and burned down his house, causing him to flee to British lines, abandoning his wife in the process.
[src:vis-viva/benjamin-thompson] He became a political and military advisor to General Thomas Gage (to whom Thompson was already passing information on Patriots), and later assisted Lord George Germain in organizing and provisioning Loyalist military units.
[src:vis-viva/benjamin-thompson] In 1781, Thompson raised his own military unit, the King's American Dragoons, which was primarily stationed on Long Island in 1782 and early 1783, where they became notorious for demolishing a church and burial ground in order to erect Fort Golgotha in Huntington, New York.
[src:vis-viva/benjamin-thompson] During his military career, Thompson conducted experiments to measure the force of gunpowder, the results of which were widely acclaimed when published in 1781 in the *Philosophical Transactions* of the Royal Society.
[src:vis-viva/benjamin-thompson] In 1779, he was elected a Fellow of the Royal Society In 1780 Thompson was appointed as Under-Secretary of the Northern Department in the British Government.
[src:vis-viva/benjamin-thompson] But he left abruptly in the following year and traveled to North America as Lieutenant Colonel of the King's American Dragoons.
[src:vis-viva/benjamin-thompson] When the American Revolutionary War came to an end, he returned to England and successfully applied to become full colonel.
[src:vis-viva/benjamin-thompson] In 1783 he had a portrait painted of himself by Thomas Gainsborough, which is now on display in the Fogg Art Museum.
[src:vis-viva/benjamin-thompson] On 23 February 1784, George III conferred upon him the honor of knighthood.
[src:vis-viva/benjamin-thompson] In 1785, he moved to Bavaria where he became an *aide-de-camp* to the Prince-elector Charles Theodore.
[src:vis-viva/benjamin-thompson] He spent eleven years in Bavaria, reorganizing the army and establishing workhouses for the poor.
[src:vis-viva/benjamin-thompson] He also invented Rumford's Soup, a soup for the poor, and established the cultivation of the potato in Bavaria.
[src:vis-viva/benjamin-thompson] He studied methods of cooking, heating, and lighting, including the relative costs and efficiencies of wax candles, tallow candles, and oil lamps.
[src:vis-viva/benjamin-thompson] On Prince Charles' behalf he created the Englischer Garten in Munich in 1789; it remains today and is known as one of the largest urban public parks in the world.
[src:vis-viva/benjamin-thompson] He was elected a Foreign Honorary Member of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences in 1789.
[src:vis-viva/benjamin-thompson] For his efforts, in 1791 Thompson was made an Imperial Count, becoming *Reichsgraf von Rumford*.
[src:vis-viva/benjamin-thompson] He took the name "Rumford" after the town of Rumford, New Hampshire, which was an older name for Concord where he had been married.
[src:vis-viva/benjamin-thompson] His experiments on gunnery and explosives led to an interest in heat.
[src:vis-viva/benjamin-thompson] He devised a method for measuring the specific heat of a solid substance but was disappointed when Johan Wilcke published his parallel discovery first.
[src:vis-viva/benjamin-thompson] Thompson next investigated the insulating properties of various materials, including fur, wool and feathers.
[src:vis-viva/benjamin-thompson] He correctly deduced that the insulating properties of these natural materials arise from the fact that they inhibit the convection of air.
[src:vis-viva/benjamin-thompson] He then inferred — incorrectly — that air and, in fact, all gases, were perfect non-conductors of heat.
[src:vis-viva/benjamin-thompson] He further saw this as evidence of the argument from design, contending that divine providence had arranged for fur on animals in such a way as to guarantee their comfort.
[src:vis-viva/benjamin-thompson] In 1797, he extended his claim about non-conductivity to liquids.
[src:vis-viva/benjamin-thompson] The idea raised considerable objections from the scientific establishment, John Dalton and John Leslie making particularly forthright attacks.
[src:vis-viva/benjamin-thompson] Instrumentation far exceeding anything available in terms of accuracy and precision would have been needed to verify Thompson's claim.
[src:vis-viva/benjamin-thompson] Again, he seems to have been influenced by his theological beliefs, and historian of science D.
[src:vis-viva/benjamin-thompson] Cardwell speculated that Thompson wished to grant water a privileged and providential status in the regulation of human life.
[src:vis-viva/benjamin-thompson] He is considered the founder of the sous-vide food preparation method owing to his experiment with a mutton shoulder.
[src:vis-viva/benjamin-thompson] He described this method in one of his essays.
[src:vis-viva/benjamin-thompson] Rumford's most important scientific work took place in Munich, and centred on the nature of heat, which he contended in "An Inquiry Concerning the Source of the Heat Which Is Excited by Friction" (1798) was not the caloric of then-current scientific thinking but a form of *motion*.
[src:vis-viva/benjamin-thompson] Rumford had observed the frictional heat generated by boring cannon at the arsenal in Munich.
[src:vis-viva/benjamin-thompson] Rumford immersed a cannon barrel in water and arranged for a specially blunted boring tool.
[src:vis-viva/benjamin-thompson] He showed that the water could be boiled within roughly two and a half hours and that the supply of frictional heat was seemingly inexhaustible.
[src:vis-viva/benjamin-thompson] Rumford confirmed that no physical change had taken place in the material of the cannon by comparing the specific heats of the material machined away and that remaining.
[src:vis-viva/benjamin-thompson] Rumford argued that the seemingly indefinite generation of heat was incompatible with the caloric theory.
[src:vis-viva/benjamin-thompson] He contended that the only thing communicated to the barrel was motion.
[src:vis-viva/benjamin-thompson] Rumford made no attempt to further quantify the heat generated or to measure the mechanical equivalent of heat.
[src:vis-viva/benjamin-thompson] Though this work met with a hostile reception, it was subsequently important in establishing the laws of conservation of energy later in the 19th century.
[src:vis-viva/benjamin-thompson] He explained Pictet's experiment, which demonstrates the reflection of cold, by supposing that all bodies emit invisible rays, undulations in the ethereal fluid.
[src:vis-viva/benjamin-thompson] He did experiments to support his theories of calorific and frigorific radiation and said the communication of heat was the net effect of calorific (hot) rays and frigorific (cold) rays and the rays emitted by the object.
[src:vis-viva/benjamin-thompson] When an object absorbs radiation from a warmer object (calorific rays) its temperature rises, and when it absorbs radiation from a colder object (frigorific rays) its temperature falls.
[src:vis-viva/benjamin-thompson] See note 8, "An enquiry concerning the nature of heat and the mode of its communication" Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society, starting at page 112.
[src:vis-viva/benjamin-thompson] Thompson was an active and prolific inventor, developing improvements for chimneys, fireplaces and industrial furnaces, as well as inventing a double boiler, a kitchen range, and a coffee drip-press pot roughly between 1810 and 1814.
[src:vis-viva/benjamin-thompson] He invented a percolating coffee pot following his pioneering work with the Bavarian Army, where he improved the diet of the soldiers (Rumford's Soup) as well as their clothes.
[src:vis-viva/benjamin-thompson] The Rumford fireplace created a sensation in London when he introduced the idea of restricting the chimney opening to increase the updraught, which was a much more efficient way to heat a room than earlier fireplaces.
[src:vis-viva/benjamin-thompson] He and his workers modified fireplaces by inserting bricks into the hearth to make the side walls angled, and added a choke to the chimney to increase the speed of air going up the flue.
[src:vis-viva/benjamin-thompson] The effect was to produce a streamlined air flow, so all the smoke would go up into the chimney rather than lingering and entering the room.
[src:vis-viva/benjamin-thompson] It also had the effect of increasing the efficiency of the fire, and gave extra control of the rate of combustion of the fuel, whether wood or coal.
[src:vis-viva/benjamin-thompson] Many fashionable London houses were modified to his instructions, and became smoke-free.
[src:vis-viva/benjamin-thompson] Thomas Jefferson used the Rumford fireplace design at Monticello.
[src:vis-viva/benjamin-thompson] Thompson became a celebrity when news of his success spread.
[src:vis-viva/benjamin-thompson] His work was also very profitable, and much imitated when he published his analysis of the way chimneys worked.
[src:vis-viva/benjamin-thompson] In many ways, he was similar to Benjamin Franklin, who also invented a new kind of heating stove.
[src:vis-viva/benjamin-thompson] The retention of heat was a recurring theme in his work, as he is also credited with the invention of thermal underwear.
[src:vis-viva/benjamin-thompson] Thompson also significantly improved the design of kilns used to produce quicklime, and Rumford furnaces were soon being constructed throughout Europe.
[src:vis-viva/benjamin-thompson] The key innovation involved separating the burning fuel from the limestone, so that the lime produced by the heat of the furnace was not contaminated by ash from the fire.
[src:vis-viva/benjamin-thompson] Rumford worked in photometry, the measurement of light.
[src:vis-viva/benjamin-thompson] He made a photometer and introduced the standard candle, the predecessor of the candela, as a unit of luminous intensity.
[src:vis-viva/benjamin-thompson] His standard candle was made from the oil of a sperm whale, to rigid specifications.
[src:vis-viva/benjamin-thompson] He also published studies of "illusory" or subjective complementary colours, induced by the shadows created by two lights, one white and one coloured; these observations were cited and generalized by Michel-Eugène Chevreul as his "law of simultaneous colour contrast" in 1839.
[src:vis-viva/benjamin-thompson] After 1799, he divided his time between France and England.
[src:vis-viva/benjamin-thompson] With Sir Joseph Banks, he established the Royal Institution of Great Britain in 1799.
[src:vis-viva/benjamin-thompson] The pair chose Sir Humphry Davy as the first lecturer.
[src:vis-viva/benjamin-thompson] The institution flourished and became world-famous as a result of Davy's pioneering research.
[src:vis-viva/benjamin-thompson] His assistant, Michael Faraday, established the Institution as a premier research laboratory, and also justly famous for its series of public lectures popularizing science.
[src:vis-viva/benjamin-thompson] That tradition continues to the present, and the Royal Institution Christmas lectures attract large audiences through their TV broadcasts.
[src:vis-viva/benjamin-thompson] Thompson endowed the Rumford medals of the Royal Society and the American Academy of Arts and Sciences, and endowed the Rumford Chair of Physics at Harvard University.
[src:vis-viva/benjamin-thompson] In 1803, he was elected a foreign member of the Royal Swedish Academy of Sciences, and as a member of the American Philosophical Society.
[src:vis-viva/benjamin-thompson] In 1772, Thompson married a rich and well-connected widow, an heiress named Sarah Rolfe (née Walker).
[src:vis-viva/benjamin-thompson] Thompson abandoned his American wife, Sarah, at the outbreak of the American Revolution; she died in 1792.
[src:vis-viva/benjamin-thompson] After several affairs and a close friendship with Lady Emily (Amelia) Mary Lamb Temple (21 April 1787...11 September 1869), Viscountess Palmerston,(born Mary Mee), in 1804, he married Marie-Anne Lavoisier, the widow of the great French chemist Antoine Lavoisier.
[src:vis-viva/benjamin-thompson] Thompson separated from his second wife after three years, but he settled in Paris and continued his scientific work until his death on 21 August 1814.
[src:vis-viva/benjamin-thompson] Thompson is buried in the small cemetery of Auteuil in Paris, just across from Adrien-Marie Legendre.
[src:vis-viva/benjamin-thompson] Upon his death, his daughter from his first marriage, Sarah Thompson, inherited his title as Countess Rumford.
[src:vis-viva/benjamin-thompson] Some periodicals and satirical publications of Rumford’s time made references that associated him with men who were publicly linked to homosexuality, notably George Germain, 1st Viscount Sackville..
[src:vis-viva/benjamin-thompson] Rumford’s surviving letters and papers do not contain evidence of same-sex relationships, and no independent contemporary documentation corroborates the claims.
[src:vis-viva/best-of-all-possible-worlds] The claim that the actual world is the best of all possible worlds is the central argument in Leibniz's theodicy, or his attempt to solve the problem of evil.
[src:vis-viva/best-of-all-possible-worlds] In Leibniz's works, the argument about the best of all possible worlds appears in the context of his *theodicy*, a word that he coined by combining the Greek words *Theos*, 'God', and *dikē*, 'justice'.
[src:vis-viva/best-of-all-possible-worlds] Since this is a very compact exposition, the remainder of this section will explain the argument in more words.
[src:vis-viva/best-of-all-possible-worlds] While the text refers to "possible universes", this article will often adopt the more common usage "possible worlds", which refers to the same thing, which is explained next.
[src:vis-viva/best-of-all-possible-worlds] Possible worlds, according to Leibniz's theory, are combinations of beings which are possible together, that is, compossible.
[src:vis-viva/best-of-all-possible-worlds] A being is *possible*, for Leibniz, when it is logically possible, i.e., when its definition involves no contradiction.
[src:vis-viva/best-of-all-possible-worlds] For example, a *married bachelor* is *impossible* because a "bachelor" is, by definition, an unmarried man, which contradicts "married".
[src:vis-viva/best-of-all-possible-worlds] But a *unicorn*, if defined as a horse with a horn, contains no contradiction, so that such a being is *possible*, even if none exist in the actual world.
[src:vis-viva/best-of-all-possible-worlds] Beings are *possible together*, in turn, when they do not enter into contradiction with *each other*.
[src:vis-viva/best-of-all-possible-worlds] For instance, it is *logically* possible that a meteor might have fallen from the sky onto Wikipedia founder Jimmy Wales's head soon after he was born, killing him.
[src:vis-viva/best-of-all-possible-worlds] But it is *not* logically possible that what happens in a given world (e.g. that Jimmy Wales founded Wikipedia) also does *not* happen in the same world (i.e. that Jimmy Wales did *not* found Wikipedia).
[src:vis-viva/best-of-all-possible-worlds] While both of these events are logically possible *in themselves*, they are not logically possible *together*, or *compossible* – so, they cannot form part of the same possible world.
[src:vis-viva/best-of-all-possible-worlds] Leibniz claims in §53, then, that there are infinitely many of these possible worlds, or combinations of compossible beings, in the ideas of God.
[src:vis-viva/best-of-all-possible-worlds] These are the worlds which God *could* possibly bring into existence, since not even God, according to Leibniz, could create a world which contains a contradiction.
[src:vis-viva/best-of-all-possible-worlds] Although God cannot create a self-contradictory world, he is all-powerful and all-knowing, as emphasized in §55.
[src:vis-viva/best-of-all-possible-worlds] He cannot be prevented from creating a world by not knowing about it, or by lacking the power to make it.
[src:vis-viva/best-of-all-possible-worlds] Given these assumptions, it might seem that God could create just any one of the worlds.
[src:vis-viva/best-of-all-possible-worlds] And since there are infinitely many possible worlds, it might seem that, just as there is no greatest among the infinitely many numbers, there is no best of the possible worlds.
[src:vis-viva/best-of-all-possible-worlds] Leibniz rejects these possibilities by appealing to the Principle of Sufficient Reason (PSR), a central principle of his philosophical system.
[src:vis-viva/best-of-all-possible-worlds] Since Leibniz adopted his principle, he could not admit that God chose to create this world rather than another – that God's choice was "thus and not otherwise" – *for no reason,* or "arbitrarily".
[src:vis-viva/best-of-all-possible-worlds] Leibniz then claims that the *only* possible reason for the choice between these possible worlds is "the fitness or the degree of perfection" which they possess – i.e., the quality which makes worlds better than others, so that the world with the greatness "fitness" or "perfection" is the best one.
[src:vis-viva/best-of-all-possible-worlds] As the philosophers Michael Murray and Sean Greenberg interpreted it, this claim may be understood by the consideration that basing the choice on any *other* quality about the worlds would have been arbitrary, contrary to the PSR.
[src:vis-viva/best-of-all-possible-worlds] Leibniz claims that God's choice is caused not only by its being the most reasonable, but also by God's perfect goodness, a traditional claim about God which Leibniz accepted.
[src:vis-viva/best-of-all-possible-worlds] As Leibniz says in §55, God's goodness causes him to produce the best world.
[src:vis-viva/best-of-all-possible-worlds] Hence, the best possible world, or "greatest good" as Leibniz called it in this work, must be the one that exists.
[src:vis-viva/best-of-all-possible-worlds] Leibniz, following a long metaphysical tradition that goes back at least to Augustine, conceived of the perfection of the universe as its "metaphysical goodness", which is identical with "being", or "reality".
[src:vis-viva/best-of-all-possible-worlds] The best world is the one with the greatest "degree of reality", the greatest "quantity of essence", the greatest "perfection" and "intelligibility".
[src:vis-viva/best-of-all-possible-worlds] According to this tradition, "evil, though real, is not a 'thing', but rather a direction away from the goodness of the One"; evil is the absence of good, and accordingly, it is technically wrong to say that God *created evil*, properly speaking.
[src:vis-viva/best-of-all-possible-worlds] Rather, he created a world which was *imperfectly good*.
[src:vis-viva/best-of-all-possible-worlds] According to the *privation theory of evil*, all examples of evils are analysed as consisting in the absence of some good that ought to be there, or is natural to a thing – for instance, disease is the absence of health, blindness is the absence of sight, and vice is the absence of virtue.
[src:vis-viva/best-of-all-possible-worlds] Evil may be said to exist in the same way the hole of a donut exists: the donut was created, but the hole itself was not *made*, it was just never filled in – it is an absence.
[src:vis-viva/best-of-all-possible-worlds] And just as the hole could not exist without the donut, evil is parasitic upon good, since it is the corruption of a *good* nature.
[src:vis-viva/best-of-all-possible-worlds] Leibniz did, nevertheless, concede that God has created a world with evil in it, and could have created a world without it.
[src:vis-viva/best-of-all-possible-worlds] He claimed, however, that the existence of evil does not necessarily mean a worse world, so that this is still the best world that God could have made.
[src:vis-viva/best-of-all-possible-worlds] In fact, Leibniz claimed that the presence of evil may make for a *better* world, insofar as "it may happen that the evil is accompanied by a greater good" – as he said, "an imperfection in the part may be required for a perfection in the whole".
[src:vis-viva/best-of-all-possible-worlds] In light of the conceptual tools that have already been explained, this claim may be phrased as stating that there are goods in the universe which would not be *compossible* with the prevention of certain evils.
[src:vis-viva/best-of-all-possible-worlds] This claim, which may seem counterintuitive, was elucidated by Leibniz in various ways.
[src:vis-viva/best-of-all-possible-worlds] In other works, Leibniz also used his broader theory that there are no "purely extrinsic denominations" – everything that may be said about something is *essential* to it.
[src:vis-viva/best-of-all-possible-worlds] So, according to Leibniz, it is technically wrong to say that "I would be better off" in another possible world: each individual is *world-bound*, so that, if God had not actualized this specific world, *I* would not exist at all.
[src:vis-viva/best-of-all-possible-worlds] And even if, due to my great personal suffering, I should think that it would be better *for me* to not exist, it would nevertheless be worse for the *rest* of the universe, since this world is the best possible world, as was proved.
[src:vis-viva/best-of-all-possible-worlds] Leibniz also applied his theory of the best of all possible worlds to solve the problem of induction.
[src:vis-viva/best-of-all-possible-worlds] Out of all possible worlds, God has chosen "the most perfect, that is to say, the one which is at the same time the simplest in hypotheses and the richest in phenomena".
[src:vis-viva/best-of-all-possible-worlds] (*Discourse on Metaphysics*, §6) This justifies human beings in choosing to believe, out of the available theories, those which are simplest and have the most explanatory power.
[src:vis-viva/best-of-all-possible-worlds] The philosopher Calvin Normore has claimed that, according to the Stoics, this is the best of all possible worlds, and that this opinion was shared by Peter Abelard.
[src:vis-viva/best-of-all-possible-worlds] Avicenna argued that divine providence ensures that this is the best of all possible worlds.
[src:vis-viva/best-of-all-possible-worlds] Following the devastating Lisbon Earthquake (1 November 1755), which occurred decades after the publication of the *Theodicy* (1710), Leibniz's philosophical optimism and theodicy incurred considerable criticism both from his fellow Enlightenment philosophers and from Christian theologians.
[src:vis-viva/best-of-all-possible-worlds] Critics of Leibniz argue that the world contains an amount of suffering too great to permit belief in philosophical optimism.
[src:vis-viva/best-of-all-possible-worlds] The claim that we live in the best of all possible worlds drew scorn most notably from Voltaire, who lampooned it in his comic novella *Candide* by having the character Dr.
[src:vis-viva/best-of-all-possible-worlds] Pangloss (a parody of Leibniz and Maupertuis) repeat it like a mantra when great catastrophes keep happening to him and the titular protagonist.
[src:vis-viva/best-of-all-possible-worlds] Derived from this character, the adjective "Panglossian" describes a person who believes that the actual world is the best possible one, or is otherwise excessively optimistic.
[src:vis-viva/best-of-all-possible-worlds] Du Bois-Reymond believed that Charles Darwin supported a version of Leibniz's perfect world, since every organism can be understood as relatively adapted to its environment at any point in its evolution.
[src:vis-viva/best-of-all-possible-worlds] Arthur Schopenhauer argued, contrary to Leibniz, that our world must be the *worst* of all possible worlds, because if it were only a little worse, it could not continue to exist.
[src:vis-viva/best-of-all-possible-worlds] The *Theodicy* was deemed illogical by the philosopher Bertrand Russell.
[src:vis-viva/best-of-all-possible-worlds] Russell argues that moral and physical evil must result from metaphysical evil (imperfection).
[src:vis-viva/best-of-all-possible-worlds] But imperfection is merely limitation; if existence is good, as Leibniz maintains, then the mere existence of evil requires that evil also be good.
[src:vis-viva/best-of-all-possible-worlds] In addition, libertarian Christian theology (not related to political libertarianism) defines sin as not necessary but contingent, the result of free will.
[src:vis-viva/best-of-all-possible-worlds] Russell maintains that Leibniz failed to logically show that metaphysical necessity (divine will) and human free will are not incompatible or contradictory.
[src:vis-viva/best-of-all-possible-worlds] He also claims that when Leibniz analyzes the propositions, he is "ambiguous or doubtful..." (O'Briant).
[src:vis-viva/best-of-all-possible-worlds] That is, Leibniz does not sound sure, and is unsure of himself when he writes his premises; and they do not work together without making Leibniz sound unsure of himself.
[src:vis-viva/best-of-all-possible-worlds] The philosopher Alvin Plantinga criticized Leibniz's theodicy by arguing that there probably is not such a thing as *the best* of all possible worlds, since one can always conceive a better world, such as a world with one more morally righteous person.
[src:vis-viva/best-of-all-possible-worlds] Leibniz's theodicy has been defended by Justin Daeley, who argues that God must create the best, and James Franklin, who argues that goods and evils in creation are interconnected with mathematical necessity and hence cannot be separated by divine power.
[src:vis-viva/boring-manufacturing] In machining, **boring** is the process of enlarging a hole that has already been drilled (or cast) by means of a single-point cutting tool (or of a boring head containing several such tools), such as in boring a gun barrel or an engine cylinder.
[src:vis-viva/boring-manufacturing] Boring is used to achieve greater accuracy of the diameter of a hole, and can be used to cut a tapered hole.
[src:vis-viva/boring-manufacturing] Boring can be viewed as the internal-diameter counterpart to turning, which cuts external diameters.
[src:vis-viva/boring-manufacturing] The boring bar may be supported on both ends (which only works if the existing hole is a through hole), or it may be supported at one end (which works for both, through holes and blind holes).
[src:vis-viva/boring-manufacturing] **Lineboring** (line boring, line-boring) implies the former.
[src:vis-viva/boring-manufacturing] **Backboring** (back boring, back-boring) is the process of reaching through an existing hole and then boring on the "back" side of the workpiece (relative to the machine headstock).
[src:vis-viva/boring-manufacturing] These are the reasons why boring is viewed as an area of machining practice in its own right, separate from turning, with its own tips, tricks, challenges, and body of expertise, despite the fact that they are in some ways identical.
[src:vis-viva/boring-manufacturing] The first boring machine tool was invented by John Wilkinson in 1775.
[src:vis-viva/boring-manufacturing] Boring and turning have abrasive counterparts in internal and external cylindrical grinding.
[src:vis-viva/boring-manufacturing] Each process is chosen based on the requirements and parameter values of a particular application.
[src:vis-viva/boring-manufacturing] The dimensions between the piece and the tool bit can be changed about two axes to cut both vertically and horizontally into the internal surface.
[src:vis-viva/boring-manufacturing] The cutting tool is usually single point, made of M2 and M3 high-speed steel or P10 and P01 carbide.
[src:vis-viva/boring-manufacturing] A tapered hole can be made by simultaneously feeding the cutting edge in both the radial and axial directions.
[src:vis-viva/boring-manufacturing] Boring machines come in a large variety of sizes and styles.
[src:vis-viva/boring-manufacturing] Boring operations on small workpieces can be carried out on a lathe while larger workpieces are machined on boring mills.
[src:vis-viva/boring-manufacturing] Workpieces are commonly 1 to 4 metres (3 ft 3 in to 13 ft 1 in) in diameter, but can be as large as 20 m (66 ft).
[src:vis-viva/boring-manufacturing] Power requirements can be as much as 200 horsepower (150 kW).
[src:vis-viva/boring-manufacturing] Cooling of the bores is done through a hollow passageway through the boring bar where coolant can flow freely.
[src:vis-viva/boring-manufacturing] Tungsten-alloy disks are sealed in the bar to counteract vibration and chatter during boring.
[src:vis-viva/boring-manufacturing] The control systems can be computer-based, allowing for automation and increased consistency.
[src:vis-viva/boring-manufacturing] Because boring is meant to decrease the product tolerances on pre-existing holes, several design considerations apply.
[src:vis-viva/boring-manufacturing] First, large length-to-bore-diameters are not preferred due to cutting tool deflection.
[src:vis-viva/boring-manufacturing] Next, through holes are preferred over blind holes (holes that do not traverse the thickness of the work piece).
[src:vis-viva/boring-manufacturing] Interrupted internal working surfaces—where the cutting tool and surface have discontinuous contact—are preferably avoided.
[src:vis-viva/boring-manufacturing] The boring bar is the protruding arm of the machine that holds the cutting tool(s), and must be very rigid.
[src:vis-viva/boring-manufacturing] Because of the factors just mentioned, deep-hole drilling and deep-hole boring are inherently challenging areas of practice that demand special tooling and techniques.
[src:vis-viva/boring-manufacturing] Nevertheless, technologies have been developed that produce deep holes with impressive accuracy.
[src:vis-viva/boring-manufacturing] In most cases they involve multiple cutting points, diametrically opposed, whose deflection forces cancel each other out.
[src:vis-viva/boring-manufacturing] They also usually involve delivery of cutting fluid pumped under pressure through the tool to orifices near the cutting edges.
[src:vis-viva/boring-manufacturing] Gun drilling and cannon boring are classic examples.
[src:vis-viva/boring-manufacturing] First developed to make the barrels of firearms and artillery, these machining techniques find wide use today for manufacturing in many industries.
[src:vis-viva/boring-manufacturing] Various fixed cycles for boring are available in CNC controls.
[src:vis-viva/boring-manufacturing] These are preprogrammed subroutines that move the tool through successive passes of cut, retract, advance, cut again, retract again, return to the initial position, and so on.
[src:vis-viva/boring-manufacturing] These are called using G-codes such as G76, G85, G86, G87, G88, G89; and also by other less common codes specific to particular control builders or machine tool builders.
[src:vis-viva/boring-manufacturing] Lathe boring is a cutting operation that uses a single-point cutting tool or a boring head to produce conical or cylindrical surfaces by enlarging an existing opening in a workpiece.
[src:vis-viva/boring-manufacturing] For nontapered holes, the cutting tool moves parallel to the axis of rotation.
[src:vis-viva/boring-manufacturing] For tapered holes, the cutting tool moves at an angle to the axis of rotation.
[src:vis-viva/boring-manufacturing] Geometries ranging from simple to extremely complex in a variety of diameters can be produced using boring applications.
[src:vis-viva/boring-manufacturing] Boring is one of the most basic lathe operations next to turning and drilling.
[src:vis-viva/boring-manufacturing] Lathe boring usually requires that the workpiece be held in the chuck and rotated.
[src:vis-viva/boring-manufacturing] As the workpiece is rotated, a boring bar with an insert attached to the tip of the bar is fed into an existing hole.
[src:vis-viva/boring-manufacturing] When the cutting tool engages the workpiece, a chip is formed.
[src:vis-viva/boring-manufacturing] Depending on the type of tool used, the material, and the feed rate, the chip may be continuous or segmented.
[src:vis-viva/boring-manufacturing] The geometry produced by lathe boring is usually of two types: straight holes and tapered holes.
[src:vis-viva/boring-manufacturing] Several diameters can also be added to each shape hole if required.
[src:vis-viva/boring-manufacturing] To produce a taper, the tool may be fed at an angle to the axis of rotation or both feed and axial motions may be concurrent.
[src:vis-viva/boring-manufacturing] Straight holes and counterbores are produced by moving the tool parallel to the axis of workpiece rotation.
[src:vis-viva/boring-manufacturing] The four most commonly used workholding devices are the three-jaw chuck, the four-jaw chuck, the collet, and the faceplate.
[src:vis-viva/boring-manufacturing] The three-jaw chuck is used to hold round or hex workpieces because the work is automatically centered.
[src:vis-viva/boring-manufacturing] On these chucks the runout faces limitations; on late-model CNCs, it can be quite low if all conditions are excellent, but traditionally it is usually at least .001-.003 in (0.025-0.075 mm).
[src:vis-viva/boring-manufacturing] The four-jaw chuck is used either to hold irregular shapes or to hold round or hex to extremely low runout (with time spent indicating and clamping each piece), in both cases because of its independent action on each jaw.
[src:vis-viva/boring-manufacturing] The face plate is also used for irregular shapes.
[src:vis-viva/boring-manufacturing] Collets combine self-centering chucking with low runout, but they involve higher costs.
[src:vis-viva/boring-manufacturing] For most lathe boring applications, tolerances greater than ±0.010 in (±0.25 mm) are easily held.
[src:vis-viva/boring-manufacturing] Tolerances from there down to ±0.005 in (±0.13 mm) are usually held without especial difficulty or expense, even in deep holes.
[src:vis-viva/boring-manufacturing] Tolerances between ±0.004 in (±0.10 mm) and ±0.001 in (±0.025 mm) are where the challenge begins rising.
[src:vis-viva/boring-manufacturing] In deep holes with tolerances this tight, the limiting factor is just as often the geometric constraint as the size constraint.
[src:vis-viva/boring-manufacturing] For highest-precision applications, tolerances can generally be held within ±0.0005 in (±0.013 mm) only for shallow holes.
[src:vis-viva/boring-manufacturing] In some cases tolerances as tight as ±0.0001 in (±0.0038 mm) can be held in shallow holes, but it is expensive, with 100% inspection and loss of nonconforming parts adding to the cost.
[src:vis-viva/boring-manufacturing] Grinding, honing, and lapping are the recourse for when the limits of boring repeatability and accuracy have been met.
[src:vis-viva/boring-manufacturing] Surface finish (roughness) in boring may range from 8 to 250 microinches, with a typical range between 32 and 125 microinches.
[src:vis-viva/boring-manufacturing] Sometimes a part may require higher accuracy of form and size than can be provided by boring.
[src:vis-viva/boring-manufacturing] For example, even in optimized boring, the amount that the diameter varies on different portions of the bore is seldom less than 3 micrometre (.0001 inches, "a tenth"), and it may easily be 5 to 20 micrometre (.0002-.0008 inches, "2 to 8 tenths").
[src:vis-viva/boring-manufacturing] Taper, roundness error, and cylindricity error of such a hole, although they would be considered negligible in most other parts, may be unacceptable for a few applications.
[src:vis-viva/boring-manufacturing] For such parts, internal cylindrical grinding is a typical follow-up operation.
[src:vis-viva/boring-manufacturing] Often a part will be roughed and semifinished in the machining operation, then heat treated, and finally, finished by internal cylindrical grinding.
[src:vis-viva/boring-manufacturing] The limitations of boring in terms of its geometric accuracy (form, position) and the hardness of the workpiece have been shrinking in recent decades as machining technology continues to advance.
[src:vis-viva/boring-manufacturing] For example, new grades of carbide and ceramic cutting inserts have increased the accuracy and surface quality that can be achieved without grinding, and have increased the range of workpiece hardness values that are workable.
[src:vis-viva/boring-manufacturing] However, working to tolerances of only a few micrometres (a few tenths) forces the manufacturing process to rationally confront, and compensate for, the fact that no actual workpiece is ideally rigid and immobile.
[src:vis-viva/boring-manufacturing] Each time a cut is taken (no matter how small), or a temperature change of a few hundred degrees takes place (no matter how temporary), the workpiece, or a portion of it, is likely to spring into a new shape, even if the movement is extremely small.
[src:vis-viva/boring-manufacturing] In some cases a movement of a fraction of a micrometre in one area is amplified in lever fashion to create a positional error of several micrometres for a feature of the workpiece several decimetres away.
[src:vis-viva/boring-manufacturing] It is factors such as these that sometimes preclude finishing by boring and turning as opposed to internal and external cylindrical grinding.
[src:vis-viva/boring-manufacturing] At the extreme, no perfection of machining or grinding may be enough when, despite the part being within tolerance when it is made, it warps out of tolerance in following days or months.
[src:vis-viva/boring-manufacturing] When engineers are confronted with such a case, it drives the quest to find other workpiece materials, or alternate designs that avoid relying so heavily on the immobility of part features on the micro or nano scales.
[src:vis-viva/calculus-ratiocinator] The ***calculus ratiocinator*** is a theoretical universal logical calculation framework, a concept described in the writings of Gottfried Leibniz, usually paired with his more frequently mentioned *characteristica universalis*, a universal conceptual language.
[src:vis-viva/calculus-ratiocinator] There are two contrasting points of view on what Leibniz meant by *calculus ratiocinator*.
[src:vis-viva/calculus-ratiocinator] The first is associated with computer software, the second is associated with computer hardware.
[src:vis-viva/calculus-ratiocinator] The received point of view in analytic philosophy and formal logic, is that the *calculus ratiocinator* anticipates mathematical logic—an "algebra of logic".
[src:vis-viva/calculus-ratiocinator] The analytic point of view understands that the *calculus ratiocinator* is a formal inference engine or computer program, which can be designed so as to grant primacy to calculations.
[src:vis-viva/calculus-ratiocinator] That logic began with Frege's 1879 *Begriffsschrift* and C.S.
[src:vis-viva/calculus-ratiocinator] Peirce's writings on logic in the 1880s.
[src:vis-viva/calculus-ratiocinator] Frege intended his "concept script" to be a *calculus ratiocinator* as well as a *universal characteristics*.
[src:vis-viva/calculus-ratiocinator] That part of formal logic relevant to the *calculus* comes under the heading of proof theory.
[src:vis-viva/calculus-ratiocinator] From this perspective the *calculus ratiocinator* is only a part (or a subset) of the *universal characteristics*, and a complete *universal characteristics* includes a "logical calculus".
[src:vis-viva/calculus-ratiocinator] A contrasting point of view stems from synthetic philosophy and fields such as cybernetics, electronic engineering, and general systems theory.
[src:vis-viva/calculus-ratiocinator] It is little appreciated in analytic philosophy.
[src:vis-viva/calculus-ratiocinator] The synthetic view understands the *calculus ratiocinator* as referring to a "calculating machine".
[src:vis-viva/calculus-ratiocinator] Leibniz constructed just such a machine for mathematical calculations, which was also called a "stepped reckoner".
[src:vis-viva/calculus-ratiocinator] As a computing machine, the ideal *calculus ratiocinator* would perform Leibniz's integral and differential calculus.
[src:vis-viva/calculus-ratiocinator] In this way the meaning of the word, "ratiocinator" is clarified and can be understood as a mechanical instrument that combines and compares ratios.
[src:vis-viva/calculus-ratiocinator] Hartley Rogers saw a link between the two, defining the *calculus ratiocinator* as "an algorithm which, when applied to the symbols of any formula of the *characteristica universalis*, would determine whether or not that formula were true as a statement of science".
[src:vis-viva/calculus-ratiocinator] A classic discussion of the *calculus ratiocinator* is that of Louis Couturat, who maintained that the *characteristica universalis* — and thus the *calculus ratiocinator* — were inseparable from Leibniz's encyclopedic project.
[src:vis-viva/calculus-ratiocinator] Hence the *characteristics*, *calculus ratiocinator*, and encyclopedia form three pillars of Leibniz's project.
[src:vis-viva/caloric-theory] The **caloric theory** is a superseded scientific theory that heat consists of a self-repellent fluid called "**caloric**" that flows from hotter bodies to colder bodies.
[src:vis-viva/caloric-theory] Caloric was also thought of as a weightless gas that could pass in and out of pores in solids and liquids.
[src:vis-viva/caloric-theory] The caloric theory was superseded by the mid-19th century in favor of the mechanical equivalent of heat, but nevertheless persisted in some scientific literature—particularly in more popular treatments—until the end of the 19th century.
[src:vis-viva/caloric-theory] Caloric theory held that heat was a conserved, weightless fluid called caloric that flowed from hotter objects to colder ones.
[src:vis-viva/caloric-theory] In the history of thermodynamics, the initial explanations of heat were thoroughly confused with explanations of combustion.
[src:vis-viva/caloric-theory] There is one version of the caloric theory that was introduced by Antoine Lavoisier.
[src:vis-viva/caloric-theory] Prior to Lavoisier's caloric theory, published references concerning heat and its existence, outside of being an agent for chemical reactions, were sparse only having been offered by Joseph Black in Rozier's Journal (1772) citing the melting temperature of ice.
[src:vis-viva/caloric-theory] In response to Black, Lavoisier's private manuscripts revealed that he had encountered the same phenomena of a fixed melting point for ice and mentioned that he had already formulated an explanation which he had not published as of yet.
[src:vis-viva/caloric-theory] Lavoisier developed the explanation of combustion in terms of oxygen in the 1770s.
[src:vis-viva/caloric-theory] On 28 June and 13 July 1783, Lavoisier read his two-part manuscript *Reflections on phlogiston* (*Réflexions sur le phlogistique*) at the Royal Academy of Sciences in Paris.
[src:vis-viva/caloric-theory] In this paper Lavoisier argued that the phlogiston theory was inconsistent with his experimental results, and proposed a 'subtle fluid' he named “igneous fluid” as the *substance of heat*.
[src:vis-viva/caloric-theory] Lavoisier argued that this “igneous fluid” is the cause of heat, and that its existence is necessary to explain thermal expansion and contraction.
[src:vis-viva/caloric-theory] The term “caloric” was not coined until 1787, when Louis-Bernard Guyton de Morveau used *calorique* in a work he co-edited with Lavoisier.
[src:vis-viva/caloric-theory] The word “caloric” was first used in English in a 1788 translation of Guyton de Morveau's essay by James St.
[src:vis-viva/caloric-theory] In his influential 1789 textbook *Traité Élémentaire de Chimie*, Lavoisier clarified the concept of caloric and introduced it to a wider audience.
[src:vis-viva/caloric-theory] The book defined an element as a single substance that can't be broken down by chemical analysis and from which all chemical compounds are formed.
[src:vis-viva/caloric-theory] Lavoisier emphasized that caloric was the *cause* of heat and therefore could not be *equated* with heat, i.e. not be the cause of itself.
[src:vis-viva/caloric-theory] Lavoisier was one of the first to use a calorimeter to measure the heat released during chemical reaction.
[src:vis-viva/caloric-theory] Lavoisier presented the idea that caloric was a subtle fluid, obeying the common laws of matter, but attenuated to such a degree that it is capable of passing through dense matter without restraint; caloric's own material nature is evident when it is in abundance such as in the case of an explosion.
[src:vis-viva/caloric-theory] In the 1780s, Count Rumford believed that cold was a fluid, "frigoric", after the results of Pictet's experiment.
[src:vis-viva/caloric-theory] Pierre Prévost argued that cold was simply a lack of caloric.
[src:vis-viva/caloric-theory] Since heat was a material substance in caloric theory, and therefore could neither be created nor destroyed, conservation of heat was a central assumption.
[src:vis-viva/caloric-theory] Heat conduction was believed to have occurred as a result of the affinity between caloric and matter thus the less caloric a substance possessed, thereby being colder, attracted excess caloric from nearby atoms until a caloric, and temperature, equilibrium was reached.
[src:vis-viva/caloric-theory] Chemists of the time believed in the self-repulsion of heat particles as a fundamental force thereby making the great fluid elasticity of caloric, which does not create a repulsive force, an anomalous property which Lavoisier could not explain to his detractors.
[src:vis-viva/caloric-theory] Radiation of heat was explained by Lavoisier to be concerned with the condition of the surface of a physical body rather than the material of which it was composed.
[src:vis-viva/caloric-theory] Lavoisier described a poor radiator to be a substance with a polished or smooth surface as it possessed its molecules lying in a plane closely bound together thus creating a surface layer of caloric which insulated the release of the rest within.
[src:vis-viva/caloric-theory] He described a great radiator to be a substance with a rough surface as only a small amount of molecules held caloric in within a given plane allowing for greater escape from within.
[src:vis-viva/caloric-theory] Count Rumford would later cite this explanation of caloric movement as insufficient to explain the radiation of cold becoming a point of contention for the theory as a whole.
[src:vis-viva/caloric-theory] The introduction of the caloric theory was influenced by the experiments of Joseph Black related to the thermal properties of materials.
[src:vis-viva/caloric-theory] Besides the caloric theory, another theory existed in the late eighteenth century that could explain the phenomenon of heat: the kinetic theory.
[src:vis-viva/caloric-theory] The two theories were considered to be equivalent at the time, but kinetic theory was the more modern one, as it used a few ideas from atomic theory and could explain both combustion and calorimetry.
[src:vis-viva/caloric-theory] Caloric theory's inability to explain evaporation and sublimation further led to the rise of kinetic theory through the work of Count Rumford.
[src:vis-viva/caloric-theory] Count Rumford observed solid mercury's tendency to melt under atmospheric conditions and thus proposed that the intensity of heat itself must stem from particle motion for such an event to occur where great heat was not expected to be.
[src:vis-viva/caloric-theory] Quite a number of successful explanations can be, and were, made from these hypotheses alone.
[src:vis-viva/caloric-theory] We can explain the cooling of a cup of tea in room temperature: caloric is self-repelling, and thus slowly flows from regions dense in caloric (the hot water) to regions less dense in caloric (the cooler air in the room).
[src:vis-viva/caloric-theory] We can explain the expansion of air under heat: caloric is absorbed into the air, which increases its volume.
[src:vis-viva/caloric-theory] If we say a little more about what happens to caloric during this absorption phenomenon, we can explain the radiation of heat, the state changes of matter under various temperatures, and deduce nearly all of the gas laws.
[src:vis-viva/caloric-theory] Sadi Carnot, who reasoned purely on the basis of the caloric theory, developed his principle of the Carnot cycle, which still forms the basis of heat engine theory.
[src:vis-viva/caloric-theory] Carnot's analysis of energy flow in steam engines (1824) marks the beginning of ideas which led thirty years later to the recognition of the second law of thermodynamics.
[src:vis-viva/caloric-theory] Caloric was believed to be capable of entering chemical reactions as a substituent inciting corresponding changes in the matter states of other substances.
[src:vis-viva/caloric-theory] Lavoisier explained that the caloric quantity of a substance, and by extent the fluid elasticity of caloric, directly determined the state of the substance.
[src:vis-viva/caloric-theory] Thus, changes in state were a central aspect of a chemical process and essential for a reaction where the substituents undergo changes in temperature.
[src:vis-viva/caloric-theory] Changes of state had gone virtually ignored by previous chemists making the caloric theory the inception point for this class of phenomena as a subject of interest under scientific inquiry.
[src:vis-viva/caloric-theory] However, one of the greatest apparent confirmations of the caloric theory was Pierre-Simon Laplace's theoretical correction of Sir Isaac Newton’s calculation of the speed of sound.
[src:vis-viva/caloric-theory] Newton had assumed an isothermal process, while Laplace, a calorist, treated it as adiabatic.
[src:vis-viva/caloric-theory] This addition not only substantially corrected the theoretical prediction of the speed of sound, but also continued to make even more accurate predictions for almost a century afterward, even as measurements became more precise.
[src:vis-viva/caloric-theory] In 1798, Count Rumford published "An Inquiry Concerning the Source of the Heat Which Is Excited by Friction", a report on his investigation of the heat produced while manufacturing cannons.
[src:vis-viva/caloric-theory] He had found that boring a cannon repeatedly does not result in a loss of its ability to produce heat, and therefore no loss of caloric.
[src:vis-viva/caloric-theory] This suggested that caloric could not be a conserved "substance", though the experimental uncertainties in his experiment were widely debated.
[src:vis-viva/caloric-theory] His results were not seen as a "threat" to caloric theory at the time, as this theory was considered to be equivalent to the alternative kinetic theory.
[src:vis-viva/caloric-theory] In fact, to some of his contemporaries, the results added to the understanding of caloric theory.
[src:vis-viva/caloric-theory] Rumford's experiment inspired the work of James Prescott Joule and others towards the middle of the 19th century.
[src:vis-viva/caloric-theory] In 1850, Rudolf Clausius published a paper showing that the two theories were indeed compatible, as long as the calorists' principle of the conservation of heat was replaced by a principle of conservation of energy.
[src:vis-viva/caloric-theory] Although compatible however, the theories differ significantly in their implications.
[src:vis-viva/caloric-theory] In modern thermodynamics, heat is usually a transfer of kinetic energy of particles (atoms, molecules) from a hotter to a colder substance.
[src:vis-viva/caloric-theory] Although caloric theory was replaced during the nineteenth century by the mechanical theory of heat and modern thermodynamics, several mathematical methods developed within the caloric framework remained in use.
[src:vis-viva/caloric-theory] In particular, equations such as Laplace's equation and Poisson's equation continued to appear in the study of steady-state heat conduction and temperature distributions.
[src:vis-viva/vis-viva] Proposed by Gottfried Leibniz over the period 1676–1689, the theory was controversial as it seemed to oppose the theory of conservation of quantity of motion advocated by René Descartes.
[src:vis-viva/vis-viva] Descartes' quantity of motion was different from momentum, but Newton defined the quantity of motion as the conjunction of the quantity of matter and velocity in Definition II of his *Principia*.
[src:vis-viva/vis-viva] In Definition III, he defined the force that resists a change in motion as the *vis inertia* of Descartes.
[src:vis-viva/vis-viva] Newton's third law of motion (for every action there is an equal and opposite reaction) is also equivalent to the principle of conservation of momentum.
[src:vis-viva/vis-viva] Leibniz accepted the principle of conservation of momentum, but rejected the Cartesian version of it.
[src:vis-viva/vis-viva] The difference between these ideas was whether the quantity of motion was simply related to a body's resistance to a change in velocity (vis inertia) or whether a body's amount of force due to its motion (vis viva) was related to the square of its velocity.
[src:vis-viva/vis-viva] The theory was eventually absorbed into the modern theory of energy, though the term still survives in the context of celestial mechanics through the *vis viva* equation.
[src:vis-viva/vis-viva] The English equivalent "living force" was also used, for example by George William Hill.
[src:vis-viva/vis-viva] The term is due to the German philosopher Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz, who was the first to attempt a mathematical formulation from 1676 to 1689.
[src:vis-viva/vis-viva] Leibniz called this very quantity the *vis viva* or "living force" of the system.
[src:vis-viva/vis-viva] The principle represented an accurate statement of the conservation of kinetic energy in elastic collisions that was independent of the conservation of momentum.
[src:vis-viva/vis-viva] However, many physicists at the time were unaware of this fact and, instead, were influenced by the prestige of Sir Isaac Newton in England and of René Descartes in France, both of whom advanced the conservation of momentum as a guiding principle.
[src:vis-viva/vis-viva] was held by the rival camp to be the conserved *vis viva*.
[src:vis-viva/vis-viva] It was largely engineers such as John Smeaton, Peter Ewart, Karl Holtzmann, Gustave-Adolphe Hirn and Marc Seguin who objected that conservation of momentum alone was not adequate for practical calculation and who made use of Leibniz's principle.
[src:vis-viva/vis-viva] The principle was also championed by some chemists such as William Hyde Wollaston.
[src:vis-viva/vis-viva] The French mathematician Émilie du Châtelet, who had a sound grasp of Newtonian mechanics, developed Leibniz's concept and, combining it with the observations of Willem 's Gravesande, showed that *vis viva* was dependent on the square of the velocities.
[src:vis-viva/vis-viva] Members of the academic establishment such as John Playfair were quick to point out that kinetic energy is clearly not conserved.
[src:vis-viva/vis-viva] This is obvious to a modern analysis based on the second law of thermodynamics, but in the 18th and 19th centuries, the fate of the lost energy was still unknown.
[src:vis-viva/vis-viva] Gradually it came to be suspected that the heat inevitably generated by motion was another form of *vis viva*.
[src:vis-viva/vis-viva] In 1783, Antoine Lavoisier and Pierre-Simon Laplace reviewed the two competing theories of *vis viva* and caloric theory.
[src:vis-viva/vis-viva] Count Rumford's 1798 observations of heat generation during the boring of cannons added more weight to the view that mechanical motion could be converted into heat.
[src:vis-viva/vis-viva] *Vis viva* began to be known as *energy* after Thomas Young first used the term in 1807.
[src:vis-viva/vis-viva] was largely the result of the work of Gaspard-Gustave Coriolis and Jean-Victor Poncelet over the period 1819–1839, although the present-day definition can occasionally be found earlier (e.g., in Daniel Bernoulli's texts).
[src:vis-viva/vis-viva] The former called it the *quantité de travail* (quantity of work) and the latter, *travail mécanique* (mechanical work) and both championed its use in engineering calculation.
